\par Introduction
\par \pard\plain \ri289\sa120\widctlpar\adjustright \f17\lang3081\cgrid {\f0 
On 18 March 1998, the Australian Broadcasting Authority (ABA) decided to conduct an investigation into whether the legitimate needs of remote and regional viewers in Western Australia were adequately addressed during the cha
nge by Golden West Network (GWN) from an analog B-MAC commercial television broadcasting service to a digital service in its WAW licence area, and from the Optus satellite to the Telstra satellite, during the period December 1997 to March 1998. 
\par }\pard\plain \s1\ri289\sb240\sa120\widctlpar\ilvl12\outlinelevel0\adjustright \b\f16\lang3081\cgrid Background
\par \pard\plain \ri289\sa120\widctlpar\adjustright \f17\lang3081\cgrid {The ABA was concerned that the public interest issues, which arose as a result of GWN\rquote 
s transition to a digital platform, may not have been adequately addressed. The ability of broadcasters to shift from one satellite carrier to another is a new situation
 for broadcasters and has been brought about by de-regulation of satellite services. Similarly, the shift from analog to digital transmission is a new situation. This issue is, however, likely to arise in the future. 
\par Until 1 July 1998, Optus was the sole 
satellite carrier for broadcasting in Western Australia, beaming in remote area broadcasting services (RABS) from its B3 satellite. Optus carried nine RABS services, including GWN, the ABC and SBS. With de-regulation of satellite broadcasting services, Te
l
stra entered the market by leasing space on the PanAmSat PAS2 satellite and offering satellite transponder space to television broadcasters. GWN decided, after six years with Optus, to change its carrier at this time and contracted with Telstra. The ABC, 
on the other hand, decided to remain with Optus. At the time of GWN\rquote s transition to Telstra, it was the only commercial television service operating in the remote area of WA.
\par }\pard\plain \s1\ri289\sb240\sa120\widctlpar\ilvl12\outlinelevel0\adjustright \b\f16\lang3081\cgrid Legislative Framework for Exercising Investigation Powers
\par \pard\plain \ri289\sa120\widctlpar\adjustright \f17\lang3081\cgrid {\f0 Under the }{\i\f0 Broadcasting Services Act}{\f0  }{\i\f0 1992}{\f0 
 (the Act) there are two main heads of power available to the ABA for gathering information. They are the power under s170 to conduct an investigation and the power under s182 to conduct a hearing. Both powers are available to the ABA for t
he purpose of exercising any of its functions and powers under the Act. The ABA decided to undertake an investigation based on the general investigations power pursuant to s170 of the Act. The s170 power provides for an investigation to be carried out qui
ckly and economically as required by s168(2) of the Act.
\par }\pard\plain \s1\ri289\sb240\sa120\widctlpar\ilvl12\outlinelevel0\adjustright \b\f16\lang3081\cgrid \page Facts and Findings
\par \pard\plain \ri289\sa120\widctlpar\adjustright \f17\lang3081\cgrid {\f0 The ABA investigated a number of issues in trying to understand the causes of the disruptive effects on viewers during GWN\rquote 
s transition from analog to digital transmission. The following matters were specifically addressed during the investigation.
\par 
\par }\pard\plain \s2\ri289\sb120\sa120\widctlpar\outlinelevel1\adjustright \b\f16\lang3081\cgrid {(a) The period set aside for simulcast of the WAW service on the analog B-MAC system and the digital system
\par }\pard\plain \s25\ri289\sb240\sa120\widctlpar\adjustright \b\f17\lang3081\cgrid {\b0\f0 The main issue of concern to the ABA in relation to the period set aside for s
imulcast of the analog and digital WAW service was the fact that many people in the licence area did not convert to the digital receiving equipment during the course of the simulcast period. 
\par }\pard\plain \ri289\sa120\widctlpar\ilvl12\adjustright \f17\lang3081\cgrid {\b\i\f0 Conclusion
\par }{\f0 There were a number of factors contributing to the de
lay for large numbers of people in the licence area making the conversion to digital. However, taking those factors into account, it is nevertheless reasonable to conclude that the two months set aside by GWN for simulcast on analog and digital was an ins
ufficient period of time for many viewers to make adequate arrangements for conversion. The fact that the two month period coincided with the vacation period and the 'wet season' served to exacerbate the problem. 
\par }\pard\plain \s25\ri289\sb240\widctlpar\adjustright \b\f17\lang3081\cgrid {\f16 b) The availability in Perth and the WAW licence area, and the progress of installation, of Scientific Atlanta digital decoders}{\b0\f16  
\par }\pard\plain \ri289\sa120\widctlpar\ilvl12\adjustright \f17\lang3081\cgrid {\b\i\f0 
\par Conclusion
\par }{\f0 GWN was aware that the commercial decoders were not available and should have known that this was having an adverse impact on the conversion process. It seems
 clear that the delays in obtaining the commercial decoders caused uncertainty among self-help communities and Shire Councils and contributed to the delays among these groups in placing orders for decoding equipment.
\par 
\par }\pard\plain \s2\ri289\sb120\sa120\widctlpar\ilvl12\outlinelevel1\adjustright \b\f16\lang3081\cgrid {(c) The level of information provided 
to viewers (including direct-to-home viewers), self-help groups and decoder dealers by GWN during the period December 1997 and March 1998}{\i 
\par }\pard\plain \s25\ri289\sb240\widctlpar\adjustright \b\f17\lang3081\cgrid {\b0 Most remote area viewers who spoke directly to ABA officers during the course of this investigation indicated that the
y had received very little information from GWN about the changes that were occurring in the shift from analog to digital. 
\par }{\i Conclusion
\par }\pard\plain \ri289\sa120\widctlpar\ilvl12\adjustright \f17\lang3081\cgrid {While it appears that GWN\rquote s information campaign may not have been particularly effective, there was nevertheless a conce
rted effort by Optus to persuade viewers to ignore GWN\rquote s advice. 
\par }\pard \qc\ri289\sa120\widctlpar\ilvl12\adjustright {
\par 
\par }\pard\plain \s2\ri289\sb120\sa120\widctlpar\ilvl12\outlinelevel1\adjustright \b\f16\lang3081\cgrid {(d) The level of monitoring by GWN of viewers\rquote 
 needs and their rates of conversion to digital receiving equipment during the period December 1997 and March 1998}{\i 
\par }\pard\plain \ri289\sa120\widctlpar\ilvl12\adjustright \f17\lang3081\cgrid {\f0 
\par GWN began monitoring the conversion process among DTH viewers, self-help sites and Shire Councils from December when the first digital decoder was enabled.}{\cs17\f0\super \chftn {\footnote \pard\plain \s18\sa120\widctlpar\ilvl12\adjustright 
\fs20\lang2057\cgrid {\cs17\super \chftn }{ GWN/Prime, submission, p16.}}}{\f0  
\par }{\b\i\f0 Conclusion
\par }{\f0 GWN effectively monitored viewers transition from analog to digital.
\par }{\f16 
\par }\pard\plain \s2\ri289\sb120\sa120\widctlpar\ilvl12\outlinelevel1\adjustright \b\f16\lang3081\cgrid {(e) The procedures adopted by GWN to ensure
 a continuity of service for remote and regional viewers during the process of changing from an analogue B-MAC service to a digital service}{\i 
\par }\pard\plain \ri289\sa120\widctlpar\ilvl12\adjustright \f17\lang3081\cgrid {\f0 
\par GWN submitted that, in addition to broadcasting over a two month simulcast period, GWN undertook to contact all vie
wers who had a registered decoder. These viewers received two information packs and if any packs were returned by Australia Post the decoder associated with that pack was contacted by B-MAC message.}{\cs17\f0\super \chftn {\footnote \pard\plain 
\s18\sa120\widctlpar\ilvl12\adjustright \fs20\lang2057\cgrid {\cs17\super \chftn }{ GWN/Prime, submission, p16.}}}{\f0  }{\b\i\f0 
\par 
\par Conclusion}{\i\f0 
\par }{\f0 The procedures adopted may, in themselves, have been adequate to ensure continuity of service had the period of simulcast been for a longer period and not covering a vacation period. 
\par 
\par }\pard\plain \s2\ri289\sb120\sa120\widctlpar\ilvl12\outlinelevel1\adjustright \b\f16\lang3081\cgrid {(f) The negotiations between Optus and GWN which occurred during the period December 1997 and March 1998, includin
g financial arrangements proposed for any additional simulcast period}{\i 
\par }\pard\plain \ri289\sa120\widctlpar\ilvl12\adjustright \f17\lang3081\cgrid {\f16 
\par }{\f0 Optus and GWN began negotiations over continuing the transmission of the analog, B-MAC service in July 1997. 
\par 
\par }{\b\i\f0 Conclusion
\par }{\f0 In the ABA\rquote s view, the public interest in resolving this matter was significant and it is not clear from the correspondence between Optus and GWN why GWN was apparently reluctant to accept Optus\rquote 
s longer term offer to retransmit the WAW service free of charge.}{\cs17\f0\super \chftn {\footnote \pard\plain \s18\sa120\widctlpar\ilvl12\adjustright \fs20\lang2057\cgrid {\cs17\super \chftn }{ Optus, submission on the ABA\rquote 
s preliminary view on whether to grant permission to Optus to retransmit the WAW signal, 9 March 1998, p5.}}}{\f0  
\par }\pard\plain \s2\ri289\sb120\sa120\widctlpar\ilvl12\outlinelevel1\adjustright \b\f16\lang3081\cgrid {(g) The availability of the government subsidy forms and the administration of the $750 subsidy during the period December 1997 and March 1998}{\i 
\par }\pard\plain \ri289\sa120\widctlpar\ilvl12\adjustright \f17\lang3081\cgrid {\f0 
\par The RTIF (Regional Telecommunications Infrastructure Fund) rebate scheme was established with funding from both the RTIF fund and supplementary funding from the federal government.}{\cs17\f0\super \chftn {\footnote \pard\plain 
\s18\sa120\widctlpar\ilvl12\adjustright \fs20\lang2057\cgrid {\cs17\super \chftn }{ Mr RJ Badger, Department of Communications and the Arts, letter 4 May 1998, p2.}}}{\f0  
\par 
\par }{\b\i\f0 Conclusion
\par }\pard \ri289\sa120\keepn\widctlpar\ilvl12\adjustright {\f0 
The scheme to assist remote and regional viewers to purchase the new digital equipment required to receive the digital signal represents substantial assistance to remote viewers. However, the scheme was complex to develop, requir
ing appropriate safeguards against misuse, and thus took some time to establish.
\par }\pard\plain \s2\ri289\sb120\sa120\widctlpar\ilvl12\outlinelevel1\adjustright \b\f16\lang3081\cgrid {
\par (h) GWN\rquote s obligations under Schedule 2, Part 3, clause 7(2)(a) of the }{\i Broadcasting Services Act}{ 1992
\par }\pard\plain \ri289\sa120\widctlpar\ilvl12\adjustright \f17\lang3081\cgrid {\f0 
\par Schedule 2, Part 3, sets out the standard conditions for commercial television broadcasting licences.
\par 
\par }\pard \ri289\sa120\keepn\widctlpar\ilvl12\adjustright {\b\i\f0 Conclusion
\par }{\f0 Under the test to be applied, GWN at all times provided an adequate signal to its licence area, or to a preponderance of its licence area in satisfaction of its licence conditions. 
